A multiprogramming OS with a focus on responding quickly to interrupts has a scheduling policy that prioritizes the CPU burst time of each process. Consider the following pseudocode for this policy: 
 `start process P1 with burst time 5;  
 start process P2 with burst time 3;  
 while True:  
     execute process with shortest burst time;
     check for interrupts;  
     sleep for 1 millisecond;  
 end while  
` What scheduling policy does this code implement?

A user-mode process is executing a system call to access a file on a file system that has multiple security protection mechanisms in place. Consider the following pseudocode for this system call: 
 `start protected mode;  
 check file permissions;  
 if (permissions OK)  
     grant access;  
 end if;  
free protected mode;  
` What protection mechanism is being utilized here?

A centralized bank server manages transactions across multiple branches. To prevent deadlocks, the server is configured to acquire locks in the following order: 
lock account;
lock branch;
modify data;
release branch;
release account;

If a programmer inserts a temporary step before modifying data, acquiring a lock on a 'processing_queue', how can deadlocks be prevented in this revised scenario?

A system administrator needs to allocate 16 GB of contiguous memory to a massive database. To prevent fragmentation and optimize memory allocation, the administrator configures the system to use a contiguous memory pool with the following properties: 
block size = 4 KB;
block count = 4096;
segment size = 64 MB;
segment count = 256;

What is the fragmentation rate for this memory allocation scheme, assuming 1 GB of memory is allocated in 16 blocks of 64 MB each?
